The Company evaluates performance based on the gross profit of the respective business segments. Selling expenses that can be directly attributable to the segment are included
 however

 revenue generating assets are utilized across segments.&nbsp;&nbsp;Therefore

The wine industry is intensely competitive and highly fragmented.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our wines compete in several wine markets within the wine industry as a whole with many other domestic and foreign wines.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our wines also compete with comparably priced generic wines and with other alcoholic and
 to a lesser degree
 non-alcoholic beverages.&nbsp;&nbsp;A result of this intense competition has been and may continue to be upward pressure on our selling and promotional expenses.&nbsp;&nbsp;Many of our competitors have greater financial
 technical

 Nationwide we sell our products primarily through independent distributors and brokers for resale to retail outlets
 restaurants
 hotels and private clubs across the U.S. and in some overseas markets.&nbsp;&nbsp;Sales to distributors are expected to continue to represent a substantial portion of our net revenues in the future.&nbsp;&nbsp;A change in our relationship with any of our significant distributors could harm our business and reduce our sales.&nbsp;&nbsp;The laws and regulations of several states prohibit changes of distributors
 except under certain limited circumstances
 making it difficult to terminate a distributor for poor performance without reasonable cause
 as defined by applicable statutes.&nbsp;&nbsp;Any difficulty or inability to replace distributors
 poor performance of our major distributors or our inability to collect accounts receivable from our major distributors could harm our business.&nbsp;&nbsp;There can be no assurance that the distributors and retailers we use will continue to purchase our products or provide our products with adequate levels of promotional support.&nbsp;&nbsp;Consolidation at the retail tier
 among club and chain grocery stores in particular

		

			
		

We are subject to certain hazards and product liability risks
 such as potential contamination
 through tampering or otherwise
 of ingredients or products.&nbsp;&nbsp;Contamination of any of our wines could cause us to destroy our wine held in inventory and could cause the need for a product recall
 which could significantly damage our reputation for product quality.&nbsp;&nbsp;We maintain insurance against certain of these kinds of risks
 and others
 under various insurance policies.&nbsp;&nbsp;However

		

			
		

There have been periods in the past in which there were substantial declines in the overall per capita consumption of wine products in our markets.&nbsp;&nbsp;A limited or general decline in consumption in one or more of our product categories could occur in the future due to a variety of factors
 including: a general decline in economic conditions; changes in consumer spending habits; increased concern about the health consequences of consuming alcoholic beverage products and about drinking and driving; a trend toward a healthier diet including lighter
 lower calorie beverages such as diet soft drinks
 juices and water products; the increased activity of anti-alcohol consumer groups; and increased federal

		

			
		

 Many of Crimson&#x2019;s brands are issued ratings or scores by local and national wine rating organizations
 and higher scores usually translate into greater demand and higher pricing.&nbsp;&nbsp;Although some of Crimson&#x2019;s brands have been highly rated in the past
 and Crimson believes its farming and winemaking activities are of a quality to generate good ratings in the future

		

			
		


 or legal
 regulatory or market measures to address climate change
 may negatively affect our business
 operations or financial performance
 Our business depends upon agricultural activity and natural resources
 including the availability of water.&nbsp;&nbsp;There has been much public discussion related to concerns that carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases in the atmosphere may have an adverse impact on global temperatures
 weather patterns and the frequency and severity of extreme weather and natural disasters.&nbsp;&nbsp;Severe weather events and climate change may negatively affect agricultural productivity in our vineyards.&nbsp;&nbsp;The quality and quantity of water available for use is important to the supply of grapes and our ability to operate our business.&nbsp;&nbsp;Adverse weather
 measures enacted to address climate change

		

			
		

We are subject to environmental regulations with respect to our operations
 including those related to wastewater
 air emissions
 and hazardous materials use
 storage and disposal.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition
 we own substantial amounts of real property that are critical to our business.&nbsp;&nbsp;If hazardous substances are discovered on any of our properties and the concentrations are such that the presence of such hazardous substances presents an unreasonable risk of harm to public health or the environment
 we may be held strictly liable for the cost of investigation and remediation of hazardous substances.&nbsp;&nbsp;The cost of environmental remediation could be significant and adversely impact our financial condition

 limit the incurrence of additional indebtedness
 limit dividends and other distributions to shareholders and limit certain mergers
 consolidations and sales of assets.&nbsp;&nbsp;If we are unable to comply with these covenants

We have substantial intangible assets and goodwill on our balance sheet as a result of acquisitions we have completed
 in particular the acquisition of Seghesio Family Vineyards.&nbsp;&nbsp;We review intangible assets and goodwill for impairment annually or more frequently if events or circumstances indicate that these assets might be impaired.&nbsp;&nbsp;Application of impairment tests requires judgment.&nbsp;&nbsp;A significant deterioration in a key estimate or assumption or a less significant deterioration to a combination of assumptions or the sale of a part of a reporting unit could result in an impairment charge in the future

		

			
		

 &nbsp;&nbsp;Prices for our common stock are quoted on the Over-The-Counter (OTC) Market.&nbsp;&nbsp;Securities whose prices are quoted on the OTC Market do not have the same liquidity as securities that trade on a recognized market or securities exchange.&nbsp;&nbsp;An active trading market for our common stock may not be sustained in the future.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a result

		

			
		

The stock market has from time to time experienced extreme price and volume fluctuations that often have been unrelated to the operating performance of particular companies.&nbsp;&nbsp;Changes in earnings estimates by analysts
 if any

		

			
		

The market price of our common stock could decline as a result of sales of a large number of shares of our common stock in the market or the perception that these sales could occur.&nbsp;&nbsp;These sales
 or the possibility that these sales may occur
 also might make it more difficult for us to sell equity securities in the future at a time and at a price that we deem appropriate.&nbsp;&nbsp;Any disposition by any of our large shareholders of our common stock in the public market
 or the perception that such dispositions could occur

		

			
		

 Changing laws
 regulations and standards relating to corporate governance and public disclosure
 including the Sarbanes-Oxley Act and the Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act
 are creating uncertainty for companies such as ours.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are committed to maintaining appropriate corporate governance and public disclosure.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a result
 we may see an increase in general and administrative expenses and a diversion of management time and attention from revenue-generating activities to compliance activities

		

			
		

 We are an &#x201C;emerging growth company
&#x201D; as defined in the Jumpstart Our Business Startups Act (the &#x201C;JOBS Act&#x201D;)
 and have taken advantage of certain exemptions from various reporting requirements that are applicable to other public companies that are not emerging growth companies
 including
 but not limited to

		
		

			
		

			&nbsp;
		


			
		

Section 404(b) of the Sarbanes-Oxley Act
 reduced disclosure obligations regarding executive compensation in our periodic reports and proxy statements
 and exemptions from the requirement of holding a nonbinding stockholder advisory vote on executive compensation
 frequency of approval of executive compensation and any golden parachute payments not previously approved.&nbsp;&nbsp;We will retain emerging growth company status until the earliest of:&nbsp;&nbsp;(1) the last day of the fiscal year following the fifth anniversary of the date we first sold securities pursuant to an effective registration statement under the Securities Act; (2) the last day of the fiscal year in which we first had total annual gross revenues of $1 billion or more (indexed pursuant to the JOBS Act); (3) the date on which we are deemed to be a &#x201C;large accelerated filer&#x201D; as defined in Exchange Act Rule 12b-2 (i.e.
 an SEC registered company with a public float of at least $700 million that satisfies other tests); or (4) the date on which we have
 within the previous three years
 issued more than $1 billion of nonconvertible debt.&nbsp;&nbsp;Under the JOBS Act
 emerging growth companies can delay adopting new or revised accounting standards until such time as those standards apply to private companies.&nbsp;&nbsp;However
 we have irrevocably elected not to avail ourselves of this extended transition period for complying with new or revised accounting standards and
 therefore

		

			
		


 we cannot predict if investors will find our common stock less attractive because we rely on these exemptions.&nbsp;&nbsp;If some investors find our common stock less attractive as a result of our reduced disclosures

atastrophic loss to wineries
 as a result of earthquakes or other events
A significant portion of Crimson&#x2019;s controlled vineyards as well as supplier and other third party warehouses or distribution centers are located in California
 which is prone to seismic activity.&nbsp;&nbsp;If any of these vineyards and facilities were to experience a catastrophic loss
 it could disrupt our operations
 delay production
 shipments and revenue
 and result in potentially significant expenses to repair or replace the vineyard or facility. If such a disruption were to occur
 we could breach agreements
 our reputation could be harmed
 and our business and operating results could be adversely affected. Although we carry insurance to cover property damage and business interruption as well as certain production assets in the case of a catastrophic event
 certain significant assets are not covered in the case of certain catastrophes as we believe this to be a prudent financial decision.&nbsp;&nbsp;We take steps to minimize the damage that would be caused by a catastrophic event
 but there is no certainty that our efforts would prove successful. If one or more significant catastrophic events occurred damaging our own or third party assets and/or services

 which have been prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the U.S. (&#x201C;GAAP&#x201D;).&nbsp;&nbsp;The preparation of these financial statements requires Crimson to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts in the financial statements and disclosures of contingent assets and liabilities.&nbsp;&nbsp;On an on-going basis

		
		

			
		

			&nbsp;
		


			
		

and assumptions.&nbsp;&nbsp;The following areas have been identified as critical accounting estimates because they have the potential to have a significant impact on Crimson&#x2019;s financial statements
 and because they are based on assumptions that are used in the accounting records to reflect
 at a specific point in time

		

			
		

&#x2014;Inventories are stated at the lower of cost or market
 with cost being determined on the first-in
 first-out method.&nbsp;&nbsp;Costs associated with winemaking
 and other costs associated with the manufacturing of products for resale
 are recorded as inventory.&nbsp;&nbsp;In accordance with general practice within the wine industry
 wine inventories are included in current assets
 although a portion of such inventories may be aged for periods longer than one year.&nbsp;&nbsp;As required
 Crimson reduces the carrying value of inventories that are obsolete or in excess of estimated usage to estimated net realizable value.&nbsp;&nbsp;Crimson&#x2019;s estimates of net realizable value are based on analyses and assumptions including
 but not limited to
 historical usage
 future demand and market requirements.&nbsp;&nbsp;Reductions to the carrying value of inventories are recorded in cost of sales.&nbsp;&nbsp;If future demand and/or pricing for Crimson&#x2019;s products are less than previously estimated
 then the carrying value of the inventories may be required to be reduced
 resulting in additional expense and reduced profitability.&nbsp;&nbsp;Inventory write-downs of $517
000
 $0 and $50
000 were recorded during 2014
 2013 and 2012

		

			
		

&#x2014;Crimson capitalizes internal vineyard development costs when developing new vineyards or replacing or improving existing vineyards.&nbsp;&nbsp;These costs consist primarily of the costs of the vines and expenditures related to labor and materials to prepare the land and construct vine trellises.&nbsp;&nbsp;Amortization of such costs as annual crop costs is recorded on a straight-line basis over the estimated economic useful life of the vineyard
 which can be as long as 25 years.&nbsp;&nbsp;As circumstances warrant
 Crimson re-evaluates the recoverability of capitalized costs

		

			
		

&#x2014;For intangible assets with definite lives
 impairment testing is required if conditions exist that indicate the carrying value may not be recoverable.&nbsp;&nbsp;For intangible assets with indefinite lives and for goodwill
 impairment testing is required at least annually or more frequently if events or circumstances indicate that these assets might be impaired.&nbsp;&nbsp;Crimson currently has no intangible assets with indefinite lives.&nbsp;&nbsp;Substantially all of Crimson&#x2019;s goodwill and other intangible assets result from the acquisition of Seghesio Family Vineyards in May 2011.&nbsp;&nbsp;Amortization of intangible assets is recorded on a straight-line basis over the estimated useful lives of the assets
 which range from 7 to 20 years.&nbsp;&nbsp;Crimson evaluates goodwill for impairment at the end of each year

		

			
		


 which could be caused by general economic or other factors
 changes in laws or regulations that make it difficult or more costly for the Company to distribute its products to its markets at prices which generate adequate returns
 natural disasters

 we are not subject to listing standards that would require us to have a compensation committee or that would require director nominees to be selected or recommended by a majority of independent directors or a nominating committee comprised solely of independent directors.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Board believes it is appropriate to have all directors involved in setting executive and director compensation and in the process of nominating directors

 with respect to an election to be held at an annual meeting of stockholders
 no earlier than 150 days and no later than 120 days before the first anniversary of our proxy statement in connection with the last annual meeting

 with respect to an election to be held at a special meeting of stockholders
 no earlier than 150 days before such special meeting and no later than 120 days before such special meeting
 or if the first public notice of such special meeting is less than 130 days prior to the date of such special meeting
 the tenth day following the date on which public notice of the meeting is first given to stockholders.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The notice shall provide such information as required under the Company&#x2019;s By-laws
 including
 without limitation
 the name and address of the stockholder and his or her nominees
 a representation that the stockholder is entitled to vote at the meeting and intends to nominate the person
 a description of all arrangements or understandings between the stockholder and each nominee
 other information as would be required to be included in a proxy statement soliciting proxies for the election of the stockholder&#x2019;s nominees

 information concerning the stockholder&#x2019;s direct and indirect ownership of securities of the Company

 our common stock is subject to transfer restrictions that are designed to reduce the possibility that certain changes in ownership could result in limitations on the use of our tax attributes.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our certificate of incorporation contains provisions that generally restrict the ability of a person or entity from acquiring ownership (including through attribution under the tax law) of 5% or more of our common shares and the ability of persons or entities now owning 5% or more of our common shares from acquiring additional common shares.&nbsp;&nbsp;Stockholders (and prospective stockholders) are advised that
 under the tax law rules incorporated in these provisions
 the acquisition of even a single share of common stock may be proscribed under our certificate of incorporation
 given (among other things) the tax law ownership attribution rules as well as the tax law rules applicable to acquisitions made in coordination with or in concert with others.&nbsp;&nbsp;The restriction will remain until the earliest of (a) December 31
 2022

 the Board of Directors adopted a policy for pre-approval by the Audit Committee of all audit and non-audit work performed by the Company&#x2019;s independent registered public accounting firm
 Moss Adams LLP
 and has pre-approved (i) certain general categories of work where no specific case-by-case approval is necessary (&#x201C;general pre-approvals&#x201D;) and (ii) categories of work which require the specific pre-approval of the Audit Committee (&#x201C;specific pre-approvals&#x201D;).&nbsp;&nbsp;For additional services or services in an amount above the annual amount that has been pre-approved
 additional authorization from the Audit Committee is required.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Audit Committee has delegated to Chairman of the Audit Committee the ability to pre-approve all of these services in the absence of the full committee.&nbsp;&nbsp;Any pre-approval decisions made by the Chairman of the Audit Committee under this delegated authority will be reported to the full Audit Committee.&nbsp;&nbsp;All requests for services to be provided by Moss Adams LLP that do not require specific approval by the Audit Committee must be submitted to the Chief Financial Officer of the Company
 who determines whether such services are in fact within the scope of those services that have received the general pre-approval of the Audit Committee.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Chief Financial Officer reports to the Audit Committee periodically

Critical Accounting Estimates: The Company&#x2019;s consolidated financial statements have been prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States (&#x201C;GAAP&#x201D;).&nbsp;&nbsp;The preparation of these financial statements requires the Company to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts in the financial statements and disclosures of contingent assets and liabilities.&nbsp;&nbsp;On an on-going basis
 the Company evaluates all of these estimates and assumptions.&nbsp;&nbsp;The following areas have been identified as critical accounting estimates because they have the potential to have a significant impact on the Company's financial statements
 and because they are based on assumptions which are used in the accounting records to reflect
 at a specific point in time

associated with winemaking

 wine inventories are included in current assets
 although a portion of such inventories may be aged for periods longer than one year.&nbsp;&nbsp;As required
 the Company reduces the carrying value of inventories that are obsolete or in excess of estimated usage to estimated net realizable value.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company&#x2019;s estimates of net realizable value are based on analyses and assumptions including
 but not limited to
 historical usage
 future demand and market requirements.&nbsp;&nbsp;Reductions to the carrying value of inventories are recorded in cost of sales.&nbsp;&nbsp;If future demand and/or pricing for the Company&#x2019;s products are less than previously estimated
 then the carrying value of the inventories may be required to be reduced

Effective January 1
 2013
 the Company adopted amended Financial Accounting Standards Board (the &#x201C;FASB&#x201D;) guidance for indefinite lived intangible asset impairment testing. The amended guidance allows an entity to assess qualitative factors to determine whether the existence of events and circumstances indicate that it is more likely than not that an indefinite lived intangible asset is impaired. If an entity concludes it is not more likely than not that an indefinite lived intangible asset is impaired
 the entity is not required to take further action. If an entity concludes otherwise
 then the entity would be required to determine the fair value of the indefinite lived intangible asset and compare the fair value with the carrying amount of the indefinite lived intangible asset. The Company adopted this amended guidance for its annual and interim periods beginning January 1

		

			
		


 the FASB issued changes to reporting discontinued operations and disclosure of disposals of components of an entity.&nbsp;&nbsp;These changes require a disposal of a component to meet a higher threshold in order to be reported as a discontinued operation in an entity&#x2019;s financial statements.&nbsp;&nbsp;The threshold is defined as a strategic shift that has
 or will have
 a major effect on an entity&#x2019;s operations and financial results such as a disposal of a major geographical area or a major line of business.&nbsp;&nbsp;Additionally

		
		

			
		

			&nbsp;
		


			
		

the disposal transaction
 and (ii) an entity will not have any significant continuing involvement in the operations of the disposal component after the disposal transaction. Furthermore
 equity method investments now may qualify for discontinued operations presentation. These changes also require expanded disclosures for all disposals of components of an entity
 whether or not the threshold for reporting as a discontinued operation is met
 related to profit or loss information and/or asset and liability information of the component. These changes became effective for the Company on January 1

		

			
		


 the FASB issued changes to the recognition of revenue for contracts with customers.&nbsp;&nbsp;These changes created a comprehensive framework for all entities in all industries to apply in the determination of when to recognize revenue
 and
 therefore
 supersede virtually all existing revenue recognition requirements and guidance. This framework is expected to result in less complex guidance in application while providing a consistent and comparable methodology for revenue recognition. The core principle of the guidance is that an entity should recognize revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration to which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services. To achieve this principle
 an entity should apply the following steps: (i) identify the contract(s) with a customer
 (ii) identify the performance obligations in the contract(s)
 (iii) determine the transaction price
 (iv) allocate the transaction price to the performance obligations in the contract(s)
 and (v) recognize revenue when
 or as
 the entity satisfies a performance obligation. These changes become effective for the Company on January 1

		

			
		


 the FASB issued guidance on determining when and how to disclose going-concern uncertainties in the financial statements. The new standard requires management to perform interim and annual assessments of an entity&#x2019;s ability to continue as a going concern within one year of the date the financial statements are issued. An entity must provide certain disclosures if &#x201C;conditions or events raise substantial doubt about [the] entity&#x2019;s ability to continue as a going concern.&#x201D; These changes apply to all entities and are effective for annual periods ending after December 15
 2016
 and interim periods thereafter
 with early adoption permitted.&nbsp;&nbsp;Management has determined that the

 2013
 the Company and its subsidiaries were included in the consolidated federal and certain consolidated or combined state income tax returns of Leucadia.&nbsp;&nbsp;However
 were determined on a theoretical separate-return basis.&nbsp;&nbsp;Due to the Company&#x2019;s history of pre-tax losses
 as of the Distribution date the Company did not reflect a benefit for its net operating loss carryforwards (&#x201C;NOLs&#x201D;) since the Company was unable to conclude it was more likely than not that it would have been able to generate future taxable income to use the NOLs.&nbsp;&nbsp;As noted in Note 3
 as of December 31
er 31
 2014
The Company filed a California state income tax return separate from Leucadia.&nbsp;&nbsp;The statute of limitations with respect to the Company&#x2019;s California state tax return has expired for all years through 2008.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company currently has no unrecognized tax benefits
 and it is not reasonably possible to estimate the amount by which that could increase in the next twelve months since the timing of examinations
 if any

		

			
		


 no formal tax sharing agreement was entered into between the Company and Leucadia.&nbsp;&nbsp;On the Distribution date
 the Company and Leucadia entered into a tax matters agreement that governs the parties&#x2019; respective rights
 responsibilities and obligations with respect to tax liabilities and benefits
 tax attributes
 the preparation and filing of tax returns
 the control of audits and other tax proceedings and other matters regarding taxes.&nbsp;&nbsp;In general
 with respect to any periods ending at or prior to the Distribution
 Leucadia will be responsible for any federal income tax liabilities and any state or local income taxes reportable on a consolidated
 combined or unitary return
 in each case
 as would be applicable to the Company as if it filed tax returns on a stand-alone basis.&nbsp;&nbsp;With respect to any periods beginning after the Distribution
 the Company will be responsible for any federal
 state or local income taxes of it or any of its subsidiaries.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company will not be required to reimburse Leucadia for any payments made by Leucadia for adjustments to taxable periods prior to the Distribution

distribution channels

 remote sites and at on-site events

 and other sales made directly to the consumer without the use of an intermediary.&nbsp;&nbsp;The two segments reflect how the Company's operations are evaluated by senior management and the structure of its internal financial reporting. The Company evaluates performance based on the gross profit of the respective business segments. Selling expenses that can be directly attributable to the segment are included
 however
 centralized selling expenses and general and administrative expenses are not allocated between operating segments. Therefore
 net income information for the respective segments is not available.&nbsp;&nbsp;Based on the nature of the Company&#x2019;s business

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Allocation of expenses: For the years ended December 31
 2014
 2013 and 2012
 the consolidated financial statements include amounts billed/(credited) by Leucadia for general corporate insurance of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$0&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;
 &amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$(85
000)&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; and &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$305
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;
 respectively
 and for internal audit procedures related to Leucadia&amp;#x2019;s consolidated audit of internal controls over financial reporting of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$0&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;
 &amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$28
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; and &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$13
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;
 respectively.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Amounts billed for insurance were determined either by the Company&amp;#x2019;s directly determined share of third-party insurance premiums or
 if an allocation of third-party insurance premiums
 based on the Company&amp;#x2019;s relative revenues and assets as compared to Leucadia&amp;#x2019;s consolidated revenues and consolidated assets.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Costs related to internal audit services were based on actual hours spent and the internal auditors&amp;#x2019; employment and travel costs.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Subsequent to the Distribution
 the Company became responsible for obtaining its own general corporate insurance policies and internal audit services
 which resulted in additional expense as a result of standalone policies and requirements.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;&gt;Vineyard Development Costs&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; &amp;#x2013; The Company capitalizes internal vineyard development costs when developing new vineyards or replacing or improving existing vineyards.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;These costs consist primarily of the costs of the vines and expenditures related to labor and materials to prepare the land and construct vine trellises.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Amortization of such costs as annual crop costs is recorded on a straight-line basis over the estimated economic useful life of the vineyard
 which can be as long as &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;25&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; years.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;As circumstances warrant
 the Company re-evaluates the recoverability of capitalized costs
 and will record impairment charges if required.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company has not recorded any significant impairment charges for its vineyards during the last &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;three&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; years.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Taxes not on income:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Excise taxes are levied by government agencies on the sale of alcoholic beverages
 including wine.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;These taxes are not collected from customers but are instead the responsibility of the Company.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Excise taxes of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$1
045
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;
 &amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$982
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; and &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$836
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; in 2014
 2013 and 2012
 respectively
 were recognized as a reduction to wine sales.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Sales taxes that are collected from customers and remitted to governmental agencies are not reflected as revenues.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

		&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  


  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Advertising costs:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Advertising costs are expensed as incurred and were &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$158
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;
 &amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$286
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; and &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$81
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; for the years ended December&amp;nbsp;31
 2014
 2013 and 2012
 respectively.&lt;/font&gt;

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Critical Accounting Estimates: The Company&amp;#x2019;s consolidated financial statements have been prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States (&amp;#x201C;GAAP&amp;#x201D;).&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The preparation of these financial statements requires the Company to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts in the financial statements and disclosures of contingent assets and liabilities.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;On an on-going basis
 the Company evaluates all of these estimates and assumptions.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The following areas have been identified as critical accounting estimates because they have the potential to have a significant impact on the Company's financial statements
 and because they are based on assumptions which are used in the accounting records to reflect
 at a specific point in time
 events whose ultimate outcome won&amp;#x2019;t be known until a later date.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Actual results could differ from these estimates.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;

					&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 3.3pt;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;overflow: hidden;font-size:0pt;&gt;

			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;The Company also purchases additional grapes and bulk wine under one-time purchase or short-term agreements.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The total of all grapes and bulk wine purchased was &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$7
666
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;
 &amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$6

000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; for the years ended December 31

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Consolidation policy:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The consolidated financial statements include the accounts of the Company and its subsidiaries
 all of which are wholly-owned.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;All intercompany balances and transactions are eliminated in consolidation.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Cost of sales:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Includes grape
 juice and bulk wine costs
 whether purchased or grown
 crush costs
 winemaking and processing costs
 bottling
 packaging
 warehousing and shipping and handling costs.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;For vineyard produced grapes
 grape costs include annual farming costs and amortization of vineyard development expenditures.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;For wines that age longer than one year
 winemaking and processing costs continue to be incurred and capitalized to the cost of wine
 which can range from &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;3&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; to &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;36&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; months.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;

			&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;In March 2013
 Crimson entered into a &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;$60
000
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; revolving credit facility with American AgCredit
 FLCA
 as agent for the lenders identified in the revolving credit facility
 comprised of a revolving loan facility and a term revolving loan facility
 which together is secured by substantially all of Crimson&amp;#x2019;s assets.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The revolving credit facility is for up to &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;$10
000
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; of availability in the aggregate for a &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;five&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; year term
 and the term revolving credit facility is for up to &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;$50
000
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; in the aggregate for a &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;fifteen&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; year term.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;All obligations of Crimson under the revolving credit facility are collateralized by certain real property
 including vineyards and certain winery facilities of Crimson
 accounts receivable
 inventory and intangibles.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Covenants include the maintenance of specified debt and equity ratios
 limitations on the incurrence of additional indebtedness
 limitations on dividends and other distributions to shareholders and restrictions on certain mergers
 consolidations and sales of assets.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In addition to unused line fees ranging from &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;0.25%&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; to &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;0.375%&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;
 rates for the borrowings are priced based on a performance grid tied to certain financial ratios and the London Interbank Offered Rate
 and would have been &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;1.671%&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; to &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;1.988%&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; at December 31
 2014.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The revolving credit facility can be used to fund acquisitions
 capital projects and other general corporate purposes.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;No&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; amounts have been borrowed under the facility to date.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;&gt;Depletion allowances -&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; The Company pays depletion allowances to its distributors based on their sales to their customers.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;These allowances are estimated on a monthly basis by the Company
 and allowances are accrued as a reduction of sales.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Subsequently
 distributors will bill the Company for actual depletions
 which may be different from the Company&amp;#x2019;s estimate.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Any such differences are recognized in sales when the bill is received.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company has historically been able to estimate depletion allowances without any material differences between actual and estimated expense.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

		&lt;/p&gt;

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Financial instrument&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;s&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; and fair value:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Investments available for sale include Certificates of Deposits at December 31
 2014 and 2013.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;All&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; of our available&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; for &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;sale securities are &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;Level 2&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; and recorded at fair value&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;. &amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; Available for sale securities that mature greater than 12 months from original investment are recorded as short-term because the securities represent the investment of funds that are available for current operations.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;Net u&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;nrealized gains and l&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;osses
 net of tax
 on available for &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;sale securities are recorded in accumulated other comprehensive &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;loss&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Unrealized losses that are considered other than temporary are recorded in other income (expense) &amp;#x2013; net
 with the corresponding reduction to the carrying basis of the investment&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;No&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; other than temporary losses were recorded for the years ended December 31
 2014
 2013 and 2012. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;Fair value hierarchy:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;In determining fair value
 we maximize the use of observable inputs and minimize the use of unobservable inputs by requiring that observable inputs be used when available. Observable inputs are inputs that market participants would use in pricing the asset or liability based on market data obtained from independent sources. Unobservable inputs reflect our assumptions that market participants would use in pricing the asset or liability developed based on the best information available in the circumstances. We apply a hierarchy to categorize our fair value measurements broken down into three levels based on the transparency of inputs as follows: &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;div style=width:100%&gt;&lt;table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 style=border-collapse:collapse;width: 100.00%;margin-left:0pt;&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:09.00%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Level&amp;nbsp;1:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:auto;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Quoted prices are available in active markets for identical assets or liabilities at the reported date. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;div style=width:100%&gt;&lt;table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 style=border-collapse:collapse;width: 100.00%;margin-left:0pt;&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:09.00%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Level&amp;nbsp;2:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:auto;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Pricing inputs are other than quoted prices in active markets
 which are either directly or indirectly observable as of the reported date. The nature of these financial instruments include cash instruments for which quoted prices are available but traded less frequently
 derivative instruments whose fair value have been derived using a model where inputs to the model are directly observable in the market
 or can be derived principally from or corroborated by observable market data
 and instruments that are fair valued using other financial instruments
 the parameters of which can be directly observed. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;div style=width:100%&gt;&lt;table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 style=border-collapse:collapse;width: 100.00%;margin-left:0pt;&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:09.00%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Level&amp;nbsp;3:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:auto;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Instruments that have little to no pricing observability at the reported date. These financial instruments are measured using management&amp;#x2019;s best estimate of fair value
 where the inputs into the determination of fair value require significant management judgment or estimation. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:12pt 0pt 0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Financial instruments are valued at quoted market prices
 if available. Certain financial instruments have bid and ask prices that can be observed in the marketplace. For financial instruments whose inputs are based on bid-ask prices
 the financial instrument is valued at the point within the bid-ask range that meets our best estimate of fair value. We use prices and inputs that are current at the measurement date. For financial instruments that do not have readily determinable fair values using quoted market prices
 the determination of fair value is based upon consideration of available information
 including types of financial instruments
 current financial information
 restrictions on dispositions
 fair values of underlying financial instruments and quotations for similar instruments. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:12pt 0pt 0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;The valuation of financial instruments may include the use of valuation models and other techniques. Adjustments to valuations derived from valuation models may be made when
 in management&amp;#x2019;s judgment
 features of the financial instrument such as its complexity
 the market in which the financial instrument is traded and risk uncertainties about market conditions require that an adjustment be made to the value derived from the models. Adjustments from the price derived from a valuation model reflect management&amp;#x2019;s judgment that other participants in the market for the financial instrument being measured at fair value would also consider in valuing that same financial instrument. To the extent that valuation is based on models or inputs that are less observable or unobservable in the market
 the determination of fair value requires more judgment. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;The availability of observable inputs can vary and is affected by a wide variety of factors
 including
 for example
 the type of financial instrument and market conditions. As the observability of prices and inputs may change for a financial instrument from period to period
 this condition may cause a transfer of an instrument among the fair value hierarchy levels. Transfers among the levels are recognized at the beginning of each period. The degree of judgment exercised in determining fair value is greatest for instruments categorized in Level 3. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;&gt;Review of Long-lived Assets for Impairment&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; - For intangible assets with definite lives
 impairment testing is required if conditions exist that indicate the carrying value may not be recoverable.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;For intangible assets with indefinite lives and for goodwill
 impairment testing is required at least annually or more frequently if events or circumstances indicate that these assets might be impaired.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company currently has no intangible assets with indefinite lives.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Substantially all of the Company&amp;#x2019;s goodwill and other intangible assets result from the acquisition of Seghesio Family Vineyards in May 2011.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Amortization of intangible assets is recorded on a straight-line basis over the estimated useful lives of the assets
 which range from &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;7&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; to &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;20&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; years.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company evaluates goodwill for impairment at the end of each year
 and has concluded that goodwill is not impaired.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:8pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;The Company evaluates long-lived assets for impairment whenever events or changes in circumstances indicate that the carrying amount of an asset or asset group may not be recoverable.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Long-lived assets consist primarily of property and equipment.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Circumstances that might cause the Company to evaluate its long-lived assets for impairment could include a significant decline in the prices of the Company or the industry can charge for its products
 which could be caused by general economic or other factors
 changes in laws or regulations that make it difficult or more costly for the Company to distribute its products to its markets at prices which generate adequate returns
 natural disasters
 significant decrease in demand for the Company&amp;#x2019;s products or significant increase in the costs to manufacture the Company&amp;#x2019;s products.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Recoverability of assets is measured by a comparison of the carrying amount of an asset group to future net cash flows expected to be generated by the asset group.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;If such assets are considered to be impaired
 the impairment to be recognized is measured by the amount by which the carrying amount of the assets exceeds the fair value of the assets.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company groups its long-lived assets with other assets and liabilities at the lowest level for which identifiable cash flows are largely independent of the cash flows of other assets and liabilities (or asset group).&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;This would typically be at the winery level which is described in note 2 above.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company did not recognize any impairment charges associated with long-lived assets during the &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;three&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; year period ended December 31
 2014.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;

						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;

						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:02.10%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #auto;height:12.75pt;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:center;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;overflow: hidden;font-size:0pt;&gt;

		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Prior to the Distribution
 which was declared on February 1
 2013 with the shares distributed on February 25
 2013
 the Company and its subsidiaries were included in the consolidated federal and certain consolidated or combined state income tax returns of Leucadia.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;However
 the provisions for income taxes in the consolidated income statements were determined on a theoretical separate-return basis.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Due to the Company&amp;#x2019;s history of pre-tax losses
 as of the Distribution date the Company did not reflect a benefit for its net operating loss carryforwards (&amp;#x201C;NOLs&amp;#x201D;) since the Company was unable to conclude it was more likely than not that it would have been able to generate future taxable income to use the NOLs.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;As noted in Note 3
 as of December 31
 2013 the Company determined that it was more likely than not that some of the tax benefit related to the deferred tax assets would be realized and reduced the valuation allowance.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Further is noted that as of December 31
 2014
 it was determined that it is more likely than not that the remaining allowance would be realized and reduced the valuation allowance to zero.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company filed a California state income tax return separate from Leucadia.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The statute of limitations with respect to the Company&amp;#x2019;s California state tax return has expired for all years through 2008.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company currently has no unrecognized tax benefits
 and it is not reasonably possible to estimate the amount by which that could increase in the next twelve months since the timing of examinations
 if any
 is unknown.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;color:#000000;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Prior to the Distribution
 no formal tax sharing agreement was entered into between the Company and Leucadia.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;On the Distribution date
 the Company and Leucadia entered into a tax matters agreement that governs the parties&amp;#x2019; respective rights
 responsibilities and obligations with respect to tax liabilities and benefits
 tax attributes
 the preparation and filing of tax returns
 the control of audits and other tax proceedings and other matters regarding taxes.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In general
 with respect to any periods ending at or prior to the Distribution
 Leucadia will be responsible for any federal income tax liabilities and any state or local income taxes reportable on a consolidated
 combined or unitary return
 in each case
 as would be applicable to the Company as if it filed tax returns on a stand-alone basis.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;With respect to any periods beginning after the Distribution
 the Company will be responsible for any federal
 state or local income taxes of it or any of its subsidiaries.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company will not be required to reimburse Leucadia for any payments made by Leucadia for adjustments to taxable periods prior to the Distribution
 nor will the Company be entitled to any refunds for adjustments to taxable periods prior to the Distribution.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company is responsible for any adjustments or liabilities related to its California state income tax return for all periods.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;

			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;

			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Under certain circumstances
 the ability to use the NOLs and future deductions could be substantially reduced if certain changes in ownership were to occur.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In order to reduce this possibility
 the Company&amp;#x2019;s certificate of incorporation includes a charter restriction that prohibits transfers of the Company&amp;#x2019;s common stock under certain circumstances.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:8pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;

			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;The table below reconciles the expected statutory income tax rate to the actual income tax provision (benefit):&lt;/font&gt;

				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:14.24%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:2pt double #000000 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #CCEEFF;height:12.75pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;text-align:right; nowrap=nowrap&gt;&lt;div style=float:left&gt;&lt;/div&gt;11&amp;nbsp;

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

  
  
  
  
  
  

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Income taxes:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Income taxes are accounted for under the asset and liability method
 which requires the recognition of deferred tax assets and liabilities for the expected future tax consequences of events that have been included in the consolidated financial statements.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Under this method
 deferred tax assets and liabilities are determined based on the differences between the financial statements and the tax basis of assets and liabilities using enacted tax rates in effect for the year in which the differences are expected to reverse.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The effect of a change in tax rates on deferred tax assets and liabilities is recognized in income in the period that includes the enacted date.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Net tax assets are recorded to the extent the Company believes these assets will more likely than not be realized.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In making such determination
 the Company considers all available positive and negative evidence
 including scheduled reversals of deferred tax liabilities
 projected future taxable income
 tax planning strategies and recent financial results of operations.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Prior to 2013
 the Company had recorded a full valuation allowance related to its net deferred tax asset.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;As of December 31
 2013
 the Company determined it was more likely than not that a portion of the deferred tax asset would&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;be realized in the future
 and therefore reduced the valuation allowance resulting in the recognition of a net deferred tax asset of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$2
500
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;As of December 31
 2014
 the Company determined it is more likely than not that the remaining allowance will be realized in the future
 and therefore reduced the valuation allowance to &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;zero&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; and recognized the remaining &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$265
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; as a portion of the deferred tax asset.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:8pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Prior to the Distribution
 the Company and its subsidiaries were included in the consolidated federal and certain consolidated or combined state income tax returns of Leucadia.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;However
 the provisions for income taxes in the consolidated income statements have been determined on a theoretical separate-return basis.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company does not have any unrecognized tax benefits; however
 if it did the Company would record accrued interest and penalties related to unrecognized tax benefits as income tax expense.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;See Note 12 for more information.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;&gt;Inventory -&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; Inventories are stated at the lower of cost or market
 with cost being determined on the first-in
 first-out method.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Costs associated with winemaking
 and other costs associated with the manufacturing of products for resale
 are recorded as inventory.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In accordance with general practice within the wine industry
 wine inventories are included in current assets
 although a portion of such inventories may be aged for periods longer than one year.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;As required
 the Company reduces the carrying value of inventories that are obsolete or in excess of estimated usage to estimated net realizable value.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company&amp;#x2019;s estimates of net realizable value are based on analyses and assumptions including
 but not limited to
 historical usage
 future demand and market requirements.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Reductions to the carrying value of inventories are recorded in cost of sales.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;If future demand and/or pricing for the Company&amp;#x2019;s products are less than previously estimated
 then the carrying value of the inventories may be required to be reduced
 resulting in additional expense and reduced profitability.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Inventory write-downs of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$517
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;
 &amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$0&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; and &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$50
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; were recorded during 2014
 2013 and 2012
 respectively.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

  
  
  

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;

					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:right;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;$&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;As of December 31
 2014 and 2013
 the Company did not have any &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;assets&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; or &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;liabilities&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; measured at fair value on a nonrecurring basis.&lt;/font&gt;

			&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;For cash and cash equivalents
 the carrying amounts of such financial instruments approximate their fair values.&lt;/font&gt;

						&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Nature of Operations:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
