		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;The Company is in the business of producing and selling ultra premium and luxury wines (i.e.
 wines that retail for &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$14&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; to &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$25&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; and over &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$25&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; per 750ml bottle
 respectively).&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Crimson is headquartered in Napa
 California and through its wholly-owned subsidiaries owns &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;four&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; wineries: Pine Ridge Vineyards
 Archery Summit
 Chamisal Vineyards and Seghesio Family Vineyards.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Pine Ridge was acquired in 1991 and has been conducting operations since 1978
 Crimson started Archery Summit in 1993
 Chamisal Vineyards was acquired in 2008 and has been conducting operations since 1973
 and Seghesio Family Vineyards was acquired in 2011 and has been conducting operations since 1895.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Additionally
 in 2005 and 2006 Crimson acquired Double Canyon vineyard land in the Horse Heaven Hills of Washington&amp;#x2019;s Columbia Valley.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Since 2010
 Double Canyon has produced wines in a third party custom crush facility.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;References to cases of wine herein refer to nine-liter equivalent cases.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:8pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Pine Ridge Vineyards owns &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;158&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; acres and controls through leasing arrangements an additional &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;18&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; acres of estate vineyards in &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;five&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; Napa Valley appellations &amp;#x2013; Stags Leap District
 Rutherford
 Oakville
 Carneros and Howell Mountain.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Approximately &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;165&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; acres are currently planted and producing grapes.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Archery Summit owns &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;103&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; acres and controls through leasing arrangements an additional &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;17&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; acres of estate vineyards in the Willamette Valley
 Oregon.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Approximately &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;113&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; acres are currently planted and producing grapes.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Chamisal Vineyards owns &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;98&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; acres of vineyards in the Edna Valley
 California
 of which &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;80&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; acres are currently planted and producing grapes.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Seghesio Family Vineyards owns &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;316&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; acres of vineyards in &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;two&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; Sonoma County appellations
 the Alexander Valley and Russian River Valley
 of which approximately &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;307&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; are currently planted and producing grapes.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;This reflects approximately &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;21&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; acres acquired with the Montafi Ranch Vineyard.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Double Canyon Vineyards owns &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;185&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; plantable acres of vineyards in the Horse Heaven Hills of Washington
 of which &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;88&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; acres are currently planted and producing grapes
 following the sale of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;307&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; acres in May 2014
 &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;285&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; of which were plantable.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Recent accounting pronouncements:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;Effective January 1
 2013
 the Company adopted amended Financial Accounting Standards Board (the &amp;#x201C;FASB&amp;#x201D;) guidance for indefinite lived intangible asset impairment testing. The amended guidance allows an entity to assess qualitative factors to determine whether the existence of events and circumstances indicate that it is more likely than not that an indefinite lived intangible asset is impaired. If an entity concludes it is not more likely than not that an indefinite lived intangible asset is impaired
 the entity is not required to take further action. If an entity concludes otherwise
 then the entity would be required to determine the fair value of the indefinite lived intangible asset and compare the fair value with the carrying amount of the indefinite lived intangible asset. The Company adopted this amended guidance for its annual and interim periods beginning January 1
 2013. The adoption of this amended guidance did not have a significant impact on the Company's consolidated financial statements.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;color:#000000;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;In April 2014
 the FASB issued changes to reporting discontinued operations and disclosure of disposals of components of an entity.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;These changes require a disposal of a component to meet a higher threshold in order to be reported as a discontinued operation in an entity&amp;#x2019;s financial statements.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The threshold is defined as a strategic shift that has
 or will have
 a major effect on an entity&amp;#x2019;s operations and financial results such as a disposal of a major geographical area or a major line of business.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Additionally
 the following two criteria have been removed from consideration of whether a component meets the requirements for discontinued operations presentation: (i) the operations and cash flows of a disposal component have been or will be eliminated from the ongoing operations of an entity as a result of the disposal transaction
 and (ii) an entity will not have any significant continuing involvement in the operations of the disposal component after the disposal transaction. Furthermore
 equity method investments now may qualify for discontinued operations presentation. These changes also require expanded disclosures for all disposals of components of an entity
 whether or not the threshold for reporting as a discontinued operation is met
 related to profit or loss information and/or asset and liability information of the component. These changes became effective for the Company on January 1
 2015. Management has determined that the adoption of these changes will not have an immediate impact on the Company&amp;#x2019;s consolidated financial statements.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;In May 2014
 the FASB issued changes to the recognition of revenue for contracts with customers.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;These changes created a comprehensive framework for all entities in all industries to apply in the determination of when to recognize revenue
 and
 therefore
 supersede virtually all existing revenue recognition requirements and guidance. This framework is expected to result in less complex guidance in application while providing a consistent and comparable methodology for revenue recognition. The core principle of the guidance is that an entity should recognize revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration to which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services. To achieve this principle
 an entity should apply the following steps: (i) identify the contract(s) with a customer
 (ii) identify the performance obligations in the contract(s)
 (iii) determine the transaction price
 (iv) allocate the transaction price to the performance obligations in the contract(s)
 and (v) recognize revenue when
 or as
 the entity satisfies a performance obligation. These changes become effective for the Company on January 1
 2017. Management is currently evaluating the potential impact of these changes on the Company&amp;#x2019;s consolidated financial statements.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;In August 2014
 the FASB issued guidance on determining when and how to disclose going-concern uncertainties in the financial statements. The new standard requires management to perform interim and annual assessments of an entity&amp;#x2019;s ability to continue as a going concern within one year of the date the financial statements are issued. An entity must provide certain disclosures if &amp;#x201C;conditions or events raise substantial doubt about [the] entity&amp;#x2019;s ability to continue as a going concern.&amp;#x201D; These changes apply to all entities and are effective for annual periods ending after December 15
 2016
 and interim periods thereafter
 with early adoption permitted.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Management has determined that the &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;adoption of these changes will &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;not have a significant impact on the Company&amp;#x2019;s consolidated financial statements.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;div style=width:100%&gt;&lt;table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 style=border-collapse:collapse;margin-left:0pt;&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:18.00pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;height:1.00pt;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;height:1.00pt;overflow:hidden;font-size:0pt;&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:325.70pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;height:1.00pt;padding:0pt;&gt;

					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;1.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:325.70pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;height:12.40pt;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Explanatory Note:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Crimson Wine Group
 Ltd. (&amp;#x201C;Crimson&amp;#x201D;) is a Delaware corporation that has been operating since 1991.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;As used herein
 the term &amp;#x201C;Company&amp;#x201D; refers to Crimson and its wholly-owned subsidiaries
 except as the context may otherwise require.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Prior to February 25
 2013
 Crimson was a wholly-owned subsidiary of Leucadia National Corporation (&amp;#x201C;Leucadia&amp;#x201D;).&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;On February 1
 2013
 Leucadia declared a pro rata dividend of all of the outstanding shares of Crimson&amp;#x2019;s common stock in a manner that was structured to qualify as a tax-free spin-off for U.S. federal income tax purposes (the &amp;#x201C;Distribution&amp;#x201D;).&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Leucadia&amp;#x2019;s common shareholders received one share of Crimson common stock for every &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;ten&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; common shares of Leucadia (&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;24
458
368&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; Crimson common shares in the aggregate)
 with cash in lieu of fractional shares
 on February 25
 2013.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The consolidated financial statements and notes thereto give retroactive effect to the Distribution for all periods presented.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Crimson qualifies as an &amp;#x201C;emerging growth company&amp;#x201D; as defined in the JOBS Act.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;An emerging growth company is defined as a company with total annual gross revenues of less than $1 billion in its most recently completed fiscal year.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;An emerging growth company will retain such status until the earliest of: (1) the last day of the fiscal year of the emerging growth company following the fifth anniversary of the date it first sold securities pursuant to an effective registration statement under the Securities Act of 1933; (2) the last day of the fiscal year in which the emerging growth company first had total annual gross revenues of $1 billion or more (indexed pursuant to the JOBS Act); (3) the date on which the emerging growth company is deemed to be a &amp;#x201C;large accelerated filer&amp;#x201D; as defined in Exchange Act Rule 12b-2 (i.e.
 an SEC registered company with a public float of at least $700 million that satisfies other tests); or (4) the date on which the emerging growth company has
 within the previous three years
 issued more than $1 billion of nonconvertible debt.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Crimson has elected to opt out of the extended transition period for complying with new or revised accounting standards pursuant to Section 107(b) of the JOBS Act.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;This election is irrevocable.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;

 the Company sold a non-strategic unplanted parcel of land in Washington for net proceeds of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$3
902
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;
 after selling expenses.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company recorded a pre-tax gain of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$1
818
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;
 net of closing costs
 during the second quarter of 2014.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;The Company is committed to spend approximately &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$412
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; in the aggregate for vineyards under development and construction in progress.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Property and equipment:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Property and equipment are stated at cost and are depreciated using the straight-line method over the related assets estimated useful lives.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Costs of maintenance and repairs are charged to expense as incurred; significant renewals and betterments are capitalized.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Costs incurred developing vineyards are capitalized until the vineyard becomes commercially productive.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;Net gain on the disposal of property and equipment previously reported was reclassified as a component of income from operations to conform with current year's presentation.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The reclassification has no impact on previously reported net income
 cash flow or equity.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

						&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;(b)&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

				&lt;td valign=top style=width:500.50pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;height:24.75pt;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;For 2012
 the total of quarterly per share amounts does not equal the annual per share amount due to rounding.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:8pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;


		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Accounts receivable:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Accounts receivable are reported at net realizable value.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Interest is not accrued on past-due amounts.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Accounts are charged against the allowance to bad debt as they are deemed uncollectible based upon a periodic review of the accounts.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;


		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;color:#000000;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;div style=width:100%&gt;&lt;table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 style=border-collapse:collapse;margin-left:0pt;&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:18.00pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;height:1.00pt;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;height:1.00pt;overflow:hidden;font-size:0pt;&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:358.15pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;height:1.00pt;padding:0pt;&gt;

						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;

					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;8.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:358.15pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;height:12.40pt;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Due to Leucadia and its Affiliates:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Amounts that were due to Leucadia and its affiliates did bear interest at a specified bank prime rate plus &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;0.125%&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;All amounts were payable on demand
 except for the &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$45
000
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; note issued to Leucadia in connection with the acquisition of Seghesio Family Vineyards that was originally due May 13
 2013.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Unpaid interest
 if any
 was added to the principal balance on a quarterly basis.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Interest expense to Leucadia and its affiliates was &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$0&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;
 &amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$783
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; and &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$5
192
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; for the years ended December 31
 2014
 2013 and 2012
 respectively.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;On February 25
 2013
 the remaining balance of due to affiliates was contributed by Leucadia to capital.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

  
  
  
  

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Revenue recognition:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company recognizes revenue from product sales upon shipment or delivery provided that persuasive evidence of an arrangement exists
 which for sales to wholesalers is a purchase order
 the price is fixed
 title has transferred
 collection of resulting receivables is reasonably assured
 there are no customer acceptance requirements
 and there are no remaining significant obligations.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The cost of depletion allowances and price promotions are treated as reductions of revenues and can be reasonably estimated based upon experience.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Revenue from products sold through retail locations
 wine clubs and the internet is recognized when the product is received by the customer and payment is received
 based on published retail prices and applicable published discounts.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Revenue includes any shipping and handling costs billed to the customer
 and such amounts are not expected to be sufficient to cover actual costs.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;14.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Business Segment Information&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;color:#000000;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;The Company has identified &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;two&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;operating segments
 Wholesale Sales and Direct to Consumer Sales
 based upon their different distribution channels
 margins and selling strategies.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Wholesale Sales includes all sales through a third party where prices are given at a wholesale rate whereas Direct to Consumer Sales includes retail sales in the tasting room
 remote sites and at on-site events
 Wine Club sales
 and other sales made directly to the consumer without the use of an intermediary.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The two segments reflect how the Company's operations are evaluated by senior management and the structure of its internal financial reporting. The Company evaluates performance based on the gross profit of the respective business segments. Selling expenses that can be directly attributable to the segment are included
 however
 centralized selling expenses and general and administrative expenses are not allocated between operating segments. Therefore
 net income information for the respective segments is not available.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Based on the nature of the Company&amp;#x2019;s business
 revenue generating assets are utilized across segments.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Therefore
 discrete financial information related to segment assets and other balance sheet data is not available and that information continues to be aggregated.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;color:#000000;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;The following table outlines the sales
 cost of sales
 gross margin
 directly attributable selling expenses
 and contribution margin of the segments for the years ended December 31
 2014
 2013 and 2012. Sales figures are net of related excise taxes.&lt;/font&gt;
