		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;div style=width:100%&gt;&lt;table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 style=border-collapse:collapse;margin-left:0pt;&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:18.00pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;height:1.00pt;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;height:1.00pt;overflow:hidden;font-size:0pt;&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:355.55pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;height:1.00pt;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;height:1.00pt;overflow:hidden;font-size:0pt;&gt;
						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:18.00pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;height:12.40pt;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;3.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:355.55pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;height:12.40pt;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Significant Accounting Policies:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;(a)&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Critical Accounting Estimates: The Company&amp;#x2019;s consolidated financial statements have been prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States (&amp;#x201C;GAAP&amp;#x201D;).&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The preparation of these financial statements requires the Company to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts in the financial statements and disclosures of contingent assets and liabilities.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;On an on-going basis
 the Company evaluates all of these estimates and assumptions.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The following areas have been identified as critical accounting estimates because they have the potential to have a significant impact on the Company's financial statements
 and because they are based on assumptions which are used in the accounting records to reflect
 at a specific point in time
 events whose ultimate outcome won&amp;#x2019;t be known until a later date.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Actual results could differ from these estimates.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;&gt;Inventory -&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; Inventories are stated at the lower of cost or market
 with cost being determined on the first-in
 first-out method.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Costs associated with winemaking
 and other costs associated with the manufacturing of products for resale
 are recorded as inventory.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In accordance with general practice within the wine industry
 wine inventories are included in current assets
 although a portion of such inventories may be aged for periods longer than one year.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;As required
 the Company reduces the carrying value of inventories that are obsolete or in excess of estimated usage to estimated net realizable value.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company&amp;#x2019;s estimates of net realizable value are based on analyses and assumptions including
 but not limited to
 historical usage
 future demand and market requirements.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Reductions to the carrying value of inventories are recorded in cost of sales.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;If future demand and/or pricing for the Company&amp;#x2019;s products are less than previously estimated
 then the carrying value of the inventories may be required to be reduced
 resulting in additional expense and reduced profitability.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Inventory write-downs of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$517
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;
 &amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$0&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; and &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$50
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; were recorded during 2014
 2013 and 2012
 respectively.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:8pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;&gt;Vineyard Development Costs&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; &amp;#x2013; The Company capitalizes internal vineyard development costs when developing new vineyards or replacing or improving existing vineyards.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;These costs consist primarily of the costs of the vines and expenditures related to labor and materials to prepare the land and construct vine trellises.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Amortization of such costs as annual crop costs is recorded on a straight-line basis over the estimated economic useful life of the vineyard
 which can be as long as &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;25&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; years.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;As circumstances warrant
 the Company re-evaluates the recoverability of capitalized costs
 and will record impairment charges if required.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company has not recorded any significant impairment charges for its vineyards during the last &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;three&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; years.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:8pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;&gt;Review of Long-lived Assets for Impairment&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; - For intangible assets with definite lives
 impairment testing is required if conditions exist that indicate the carrying value may not be recoverable.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;For intangible assets with indefinite lives and for goodwill
 impairment testing is required at least annually or more frequently if events or circumstances indicate that these assets might be impaired.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company currently has no intangible assets with indefinite lives.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Substantially all of the Company&amp;#x2019;s goodwill and other intangible assets result from the acquisition of Seghesio Family Vineyards in May 2011.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Amortization of intangible assets is recorded on a straight-line basis over the estimated useful lives of the assets
 which range from &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;7&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; to &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;20&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; years.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company evaluates goodwill for impairment at the end of each year
 and has concluded that goodwill is not impaired.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:8pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;The Company evaluates long-lived assets for impairment whenever events or changes in circumstances indicate that the carrying amount of an asset or asset group may not be recoverable.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Long-lived assets consist primarily of property and equipment.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Circumstances that might cause the Company to evaluate its long-lived assets for impairment could include a significant decline in the prices of the Company or the industry can charge for its products
 which could be caused by general economic or other factors
 changes in laws or regulations that make it difficult or more costly for the Company to distribute its products to its markets at prices which generate adequate returns
 natural disasters
 significant decrease in demand for the Company&amp;#x2019;s products or significant increase in the costs to manufacture the Company&amp;#x2019;s products.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Recoverability of assets is measured by a comparison of the carrying amount of an asset group to future net cash flows expected to be generated by the asset group.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;If such assets are considered to be impaired
 the impairment to be recognized is measured by the amount by which the carrying amount of the assets exceeds the fair value of the assets.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company groups its long-lived assets with other assets and liabilities at the lowest level for which identifiable cash flows are largely independent of the cash flows of other assets and liabilities (or asset group).&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;This would typically be at the winery level which is described in note 2 above.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company did not recognize any impairment charges associated with long-lived assets during the &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;three&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; year period ended December 31
 2014.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:8pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;&gt;Depletion allowances -&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; The Company pays depletion allowances to its distributors based on their sales to their customers.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;These allowances are estimated on a monthly basis by the Company
 and allowances are accrued as a reduction of sales.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Subsequently
 distributors will bill the Company for actual depletions
 which may be different from the Company&amp;#x2019;s estimate.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Any such differences are recognized in sales when the bill is received.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company has historically been able to estimate depletion allowances without any material differences between actual and estimated expense.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:8pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;(b)&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Consolidation policy:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The consolidated financial statements include the accounts of the Company and its subsidiaries
 all of which are wholly-owned.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;All intercompany balances and transactions are eliminated in consolidation.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:8pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;(c)&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Cash and cash equivalents:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company considers short-term investments
 which have maturities of less than three months at the time of acquisition
 to be cash equivalents.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company had &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;no&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; short-term investments considered to be cash and cash equivalents at December 31
 2014 and 2013.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;color:#000000;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;(d) &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Financial instrument&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;s&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; and fair value:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Investments available for sale include Certificates of Deposits at December 31
 2014 and 2013.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;All&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; of our available&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; for &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;sale securities are &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;Level 2&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; and recorded at fair value&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;. &amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; Available for sale securities that mature greater than 12 months from original investment are recorded as short-term because the securities represent the investment of funds that are available for current operations.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;Net u&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;nrealized gains and l&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;osses
 net of tax
 on available for &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;sale securities are recorded in accumulated other comprehensive &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;loss&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Unrealized losses that are considered other than temporary are recorded in other income (expense) &amp;#x2013; net
 with the corresponding reduction to the carrying basis of the investment&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;No&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; other than temporary losses were recorded for the years ended December 31
 2014
 2013 and 2012. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt;Fair value hierarchy:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;&gt; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;In determining fair value
 we maximize the use of observable inputs and minimize the use of unobservable inputs by requiring that observable inputs be used when available. Observable inputs are inputs that market participants would use in pricing the asset or liability based on market data obtained from independent sources. Unobservable inputs reflect our assumptions that market participants would use in pricing the asset or liability developed based on the best information available in the circumstances. We apply a hierarchy to categorize our fair value measurements broken down into three levels based on the transparency of inputs as follows: &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;div style=width:100%&gt;&lt;table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 style=border-collapse:collapse;width: 100.00%;margin-left:0pt;&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:09.00%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Level&amp;nbsp;1:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:auto;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Quoted prices are available in active markets for identical assets or liabilities at the reported date. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;div style=width:100%&gt;&lt;table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 style=border-collapse:collapse;width: 100.00%;margin-left:0pt;&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:09.00%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Level&amp;nbsp;2:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:auto;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Pricing inputs are other than quoted prices in active markets
 which are either directly or indirectly observable as of the reported date. The nature of these financial instruments include cash instruments for which quoted prices are available but traded less frequently
 derivative instruments whose fair value have been derived using a model where inputs to the model are directly observable in the market
 or can be derived principally from or corroborated by observable market data
 and instruments that are fair valued using other financial instruments
 the parameters of which can be directly observed. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;div style=width:100%&gt;&lt;table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 style=border-collapse:collapse;width: 100.00%;margin-left:0pt;&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:09.00%;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Level&amp;nbsp;3:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=top style=width:auto;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
						&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Instruments that have little to no pricing observability at the reported date. These financial instruments are measured using management&amp;#x2019;s best estimate of fair value
 where the inputs into the determination of fair value require significant management judgment or estimation. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:12pt 0pt 0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Financial instruments are valued at quoted market prices
 if available. Certain financial instruments have bid and ask prices that can be observed in the marketplace. For financial instruments whose inputs are based on bid-ask prices
 the financial instrument is valued at the point within the bid-ask range that meets our best estimate of fair value. We use prices and inputs that are current at the measurement date. For financial instruments that do not have readily determinable fair values using quoted market prices
 the determination of fair value is based upon consideration of available information
 including types of financial instruments
 current financial information
 restrictions on dispositions
 fair values of underlying financial instruments and quotations for similar instruments. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:12pt 0pt 0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;The valuation of financial instruments may include the use of valuation models and other techniques. Adjustments to valuations derived from valuation models may be made when
 in management&amp;#x2019;s judgment
 features of the financial instrument such as its complexity
 the market in which the financial instrument is traded and risk uncertainties about market conditions require that an adjustment be made to the value derived from the models. Adjustments from the price derived from a valuation model reflect management&amp;#x2019;s judgment that other participants in the market for the financial instrument being measured at fair value would also consider in valuing that same financial instrument. To the extent that valuation is based on models or inputs that are less observable or unobservable in the market
 the determination of fair value requires more judgment. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;The availability of observable inputs can vary and is affected by a wide variety of factors
 including
 for example
 the type of financial instrument and market conditions. As the observability of prices and inputs may change for a financial instrument from period to period
 this condition may cause a transfer of an instrument among the fair value hierarchy levels. Transfers among the levels are recognized at the beginning of each period. The degree of judgment exercised in determining fair value is greatest for instruments categorized in Level 3. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;(e)&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Accounts receivable:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Accounts receivable are reported at net realizable value.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Interest is not accrued on past-due amounts.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Accounts are charged against the allowance to bad debt as they are deemed uncollectible based upon a periodic review of the accounts.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;punctuation-wrap:hanging;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;vertical-align:baseline;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;(f)&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Property and equipment:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Property and equipment are stated at cost and are depreciated using the straight-line method over the related assets estimated useful lives.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Costs of maintenance and repairs are charged to expense as incurred; significant renewals and betterments are capitalized.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Costs incurred developing vineyards are capitalized until the vineyard becomes commercially productive.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Net gain on the disposal of property and equipment previously reported was reclassified as a component of income from operations to conform with current year's presentation.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The reclassification has no impact on previously reported net income
 cash flow or equity.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;(g)&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Concentrations of risk:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company sells the majority of its wine through distributors and retailers.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Receivables arising from these sales are not collateralized.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;For the years ended December 31
 2014
 2013 and 2012
 sales to one customer accounted for approximately &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;15%&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;
 &amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;14%&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; and &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;14%&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; of total sales
 respectively.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Amounts due from this customer represented approximately &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;32%&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; and &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;26%&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; of accounts receivable as of December 31
 2014 and 2013
 respectively.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;The Company maintains its cash in bank deposit accounts that
 at times
 may exceed FDIC insurance &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;thresholds.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:8pt;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;(h)&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Revenue recognition:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company recognizes revenue from product sales upon shipment or delivery provided that persuasive evidence of an arrangement exists
 which for sales to wholesalers is a purchase order
 the price is fixed
 title has transferred
 collection of resulting receivables is reasonably assured
 there are no customer acceptance requirements
 and there are no remaining significant obligations.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The cost of depletion allowances and price promotions are treated as reductions of revenues and can be reasonably estimated based upon experience.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Revenue from products sold through retail locations
 wine clubs and the internet is recognized when the product is received by the customer and payment is received
 based on published retail prices and applicable published discounts.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Revenue includes any shipping and handling costs billed to the customer
 and such amounts are not expected to be sufficient to cover actual costs.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:8pt;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;(i)&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Cost of sales:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Includes grape
 juice and bulk wine costs
 whether purchased or grown
 crush costs
 winemaking and processing costs
 bottling
 packaging
 warehousing and shipping and handling costs.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;For vineyard produced grapes
 grape costs include annual farming costs and amortization of vineyard development expenditures.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;For wines that age longer than one year
 winemaking and processing costs continue to be incurred and capitalized to the cost of wine
 which can range from &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;3&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; to &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;36&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; months.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:8pt;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;(j)&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Taxes not on income:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Excise taxes are levied by government agencies on the sale of alcoholic beverages
 including wine.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;These taxes are not collected from customers but are instead the responsibility of the Company.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Excise taxes of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$1
045
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;
 &amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$982
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; and &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$836
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; in 2014
 2013 and 2012
 respectively
 were recognized as a reduction to wine sales.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Sales taxes that are collected from customers and remitted to governmental agencies are not reflected as revenues.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;(k)&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Advertising costs:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Advertising costs are expensed as incurred and were &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$158
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;
 &amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$286
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; and &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$81
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; for the years ended December&amp;nbsp;31
 2014
 2013 and 2012
 respectively.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;(l)&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Income taxes:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Income taxes are accounted for under the asset and liability method
 which requires the recognition of deferred tax assets and liabilities for the expected future tax consequences of events that have been included in the consolidated financial statements.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Under this method
 deferred tax assets and liabilities are determined based on the differences between the financial statements and the tax basis of assets and liabilities using enacted tax rates in effect for the year in which the differences are expected to reverse.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The effect of a change in tax rates on deferred tax assets and liabilities is recognized in income in the period that includes the enacted date.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Net tax assets are recorded to the extent the Company believes these assets will more likely than not be realized.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In making such determination
 the Company considers all available positive and negative evidence
 including scheduled reversals of deferred tax liabilities
 projected future taxable income
 tax planning strategies and recent financial results of operations.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Prior to 2013
 the Company had recorded a full valuation allowance related to its net deferred tax asset.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;As of December 31
 2013
 the Company determined it was more likely than not that a portion of the deferred tax asset would&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;be realized in the future
 and therefore reduced the valuation allowance resulting in the recognition of a net deferred tax asset of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$2
500
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;As of December 31
 2014
 the Company determined it is more likely than not that the remaining allowance will be realized in the future
 and therefore reduced the valuation allowance to &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;zero&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; and recognized the remaining &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$265
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; as a portion of the deferred tax asset.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:8pt;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Prior to the Distribution
 the Company and its subsidiaries were included in the consolidated federal and certain consolidated or combined state income tax returns of Leucadia.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;However
 the provisions for income taxes in the consolidated income statements have been determined on a theoretical separate-return basis.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company does not have any unrecognized tax benefits; however
 if it did the Company would record accrued interest and penalties related to unrecognized tax benefits as income tax expense.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;See Note 12 for more information.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;color:#000000;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;(m)&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Allocation of expenses: For the years ended December 31
 2014
 2013 and 2012
 the consolidated financial statements include amounts billed/(credited) by Leucadia for general corporate insurance of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$0&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;
 &amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$(85
000)&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; and &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$305
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;
 respectively
 and for internal audit procedures related to Leucadia&amp;#x2019;s consolidated audit of internal controls over financial reporting of &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$0&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;
 &amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$28
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt; and &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;$13
000&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;
 respectively.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Amounts billed for insurance were determined either by the Company&amp;#x2019;s directly determined share of third-party insurance premiums or
 if an allocation of third-party insurance premiums
 based on the Company&amp;#x2019;s relative revenues and assets as compared to Leucadia&amp;#x2019;s consolidated revenues and consolidated assets.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Costs related to internal audit services were based on actual hours spent and the internal auditors&amp;#x2019; employment and travel costs.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Subsequent to the Distribution
 the Company became responsible for obtaining its own general corporate insurance policies and internal audit services
 which resulted in additional expense as a result of standalone policies and requirements. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;font-size:8pt;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;(n)&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Recent accounting pronouncements:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;Effective January 1
 2013
 the Company adopted amended Financial Accounting Standards Board (the &amp;#x201C;FASB&amp;#x201D;) guidance for indefinite lived intangible asset impairment testing. The amended guidance allows an entity to assess qualitative factors to determine whether the existence of events and circumstances indicate that it is more likely than not that an indefinite lived intangible asset is impaired. If an entity concludes it is not more likely than not that an indefinite lived intangible asset is impaired
 the entity is not required to take further action. If an entity concludes otherwise
 then the entity would be required to determine the fair value of the indefinite lived intangible asset and compare the fair value with the carrying amount of the indefinite lived intangible asset. The Company adopted this amended guidance for its annual and interim periods beginning January 1
 2013. The adoption of this amended guidance did not have a significant impact on the Company's consolidated financial statements.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;color:#000000;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;In April 2014
 the FASB issued changes to reporting discontinued operations and disclosure of disposals of components of an entity.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;These changes require a disposal of a component to meet a higher threshold in order to be reported as a discontinued operation in an entity&amp;#x2019;s financial statements.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The threshold is defined as a strategic shift that has
 or will have
 a major effect on an entity&amp;#x2019;s operations and financial results such as a disposal of a major geographical area or a major line of business.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Additionally
 the following two criteria have been removed from consideration of whether a component meets the requirements for discontinued operations presentation: (i) the operations and cash flows of a disposal component have been or will be eliminated from the ongoing operations of an entity as a result of the disposal transaction
 and (ii) an entity will not have any significant continuing involvement in the operations of the disposal component after the disposal transaction. Furthermore
 equity method investments now may qualify for discontinued operations presentation. These changes also require expanded disclosures for all disposals of components of an entity
 whether or not the threshold for reporting as a discontinued operation is met
 related to profit or loss information and/or asset and liability information of the component. These changes became effective for the Company on January 1
 2015. Management has determined that the adoption of these changes will not have an immediate impact on the Company&amp;#x2019;s consolidated financial statements.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;In May 2014
 the FASB issued changes to the recognition of revenue for contracts with customers.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;These changes created a comprehensive framework for all entities in all industries to apply in the determination of when to recognize revenue
 and
 therefore
 supersede virtually all existing revenue recognition requirements and guidance. This framework is expected to result in less complex guidance in application while providing a consistent and comparable methodology for revenue recognition. The core principle of the guidance is that an entity should recognize revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration to which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services. To achieve this principle
 an entity should apply the following steps: (i) identify the contract(s) with a customer
 (ii) identify the performance obligations in the contract(s)
 (iii) determine the transaction price
 (iv) allocate the transaction price to the performance obligations in the contract(s)
 and (v) recognize revenue when
 or as
 the entity satisfies a performance obligation. These changes become effective for the Company on January 1
 2017. Management is currently evaluating the potential impact of these changes on the Company&amp;#x2019;s consolidated financial statements.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:100%;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt&gt;
			&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;In August 2014
 the FASB issued guidance on determining when and how to disclose going-concern uncertainties in the financial statements. The new standard requires management to perform interim and annual assessments of an entity&amp;#x2019;s ability to continue as a going concern within one year of the date the financial statements are issued. An entity must provide certain disclosures if &amp;#x201C;conditions or events raise substantial doubt about [the] entity&amp;#x2019;s ability to continue as a going concern.&amp;#x201D; These changes apply to all entities and are effective for annual periods ending after December 15
 2016
 and interim periods thereafter
 with early adoption permitted.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Management has determined that the &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;adoption of these changes will &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display: inline;color:#000000;&gt;not have a significant impact on the Company&amp;#x2019;s consolidated financial statements.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size=1&gt; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

							function toggleNextSibling (e) {
							if (e.nextSibling.style.display=='none') {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='block';
							} else {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='none';
							}
							}

 the highest effective rate for funds borrowed under the debt agreement as of the balance sheet date.
              
                
              

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    








        
          

        
          
            

 the lowest effective rate for funds borrowed under the debt agreement as of the balance sheet date.
              
                
              

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    

                  
                    
                    








        
          

        
          
            

 which is a bank's commitment to make loans up to a specific amount. Examples of items that might be included in the application of this element may consist of letters of credit
 standby letters of credit
 and revolving credit arrangements
 under which borrowings can be made up to a maximum amount as of any point in time conditional on satisfaction of specified terms before
 as of and after the date of drawdowns on the line. Includes short-term obligations that would normally be classified as current liabilities but for which (a) postbalance sheet date issuance of a long term obligation to refinance the short term obligation on a long term basis
 or (b) the enterprise has entered into a financing agreement that clearly permits the enterprise to refinance the short-term obligation on a long term basis and the following conditions are met (1) the agreement does not expire within 1 year and is not cancelable by the lender except for violation of an objectively determinable provision
 (2) no violation exists at the BS date
 and (3) the lender has entered into the financing agreement is expected to be financially capable of honoring the agreement.

							function toggleNextSibling (e) {
							if (e.nextSibling.style.display=='none') {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='block';
							} else {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='none';
							}
							}

							function toggleNextSibling (e) {
							if (e.nextSibling.style.display=='none') {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='block';
							} else {
							e.nextSibling.style.display='none';
							}
							}
